I don’t know what the fuck aetherpunk is, and I’m pretty sure most readers won’t know what it is. You should be spending more time describing each scene and setting things up. How big was the office when the MC stepped inside it? Was it huge? Small? Did it make him feel insignificant or claustrophobic? Taking one or two paragraphs of prose establishing the details of your background can help the reader understand what kind of a place the MC is at. Your mind may have a perfect image of what the school looks like, but we don’t. If you didn’t straight out tell me that it was aetherpunk, I would’ve thought this was just regular fantasy. The readers should never be confused.

Your dialogue seems kind of stiff, so try asking yourself if it sounds natural by you reading them out loud and make adjustments.

There’s no way you can develop a consistent style that fast. Good prose comes from a lot of practice and learning from other writers to improve. I feel that you should take more time revising the first chapter and take more time smoothing out everything before you post the story again. Quality always comes before quantity. Take your time and read physical books on writing and establish an entire setting along with a plot line that has character development scenes you’ve planned out with time before writing and transferring your ideas to text. I know this sounds tedious, but an adventure story has to have a more concrete setting and more worldbuilding than just comfy greentexts based on the real world.
I’d suggest you to start with this http://biblioteka.teatr-obraz.ru/files/file/English_cinema/How_to_Write_Damn_Good_Novel_1.pdf and take the advices to heart.
